h  .","Americanized form of Ukrainian and Jewish (from Ukraine)   Voloshin   or its Polish variant <b>Wołoszyn</b> (see   Woloszyn  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Walsh","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Aileen, Dermot, John Patrick, Kieran, Declan, Eamonn, Colm, Donal, Seamus, Siobhan, Brennan.","English and Irish: ethnic name from Middle English <i>walshe</i> (Old English <i>wælisc</i>) ‘foreign, Welsh’. This form of the name was generally more common than   Welsh  , especially in Ireland, where it originally denoted a Welsh-speaking immigrant, in particular any of the Welshmen who arrived in the wake of Strongbow's Anglo-Norman invasion of 1170. In Ireland it is sometimes also a translation of <b>Breathnach</b> ‘Briton’.","English: in Yorkshire and Lancashire the name is sometimes a shortened form of   Walshaw  ."]},{"name":"Walch","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Welsh  .","German: from the personal name <i>Walcho</i>.","German: ethnic name, a variant of   Wahl   1."]},{"name":"Wilch","meanings":["German (Hesse and Rhineland-Palatinate): unexplained.","English: apparently a variant of   Welsh  ."]},{"name":"Welch","meanings":["English: variant of   Welsh   or   Walsh  , an ethnic name for someone of Welsh origin. This is the usual form of the surname in England; the usual form in Ireland is   Walsh   and in Scotland   Welsh  .","German: variant of   Welk  .","Americanized form of German   Welsch  ."]},{"name":"Wallis","meanings":["Scottish and English: from Anglo-Norman French <i>Waleis</i>, <i>Walais</i> ‘Welshman’, also sometimes ‘Breton’ (from Old English <i>wēalas</i>, <i>walas</i>, plural of <i>walh</i>, <i>wealh</i>, originally meaning a ‘Roman citizen’ and referring to the native British population, but in Old English this term later came to mean ‘serf, unfree person, foreigner’ or ‘Welshman’). In western and central England the medieval reference is clearly to Welshmen. In Norfolk and Lincolnshire, the reference was probably to Bretons, many of whom settled in the eastern counties after the Conquest. Compare   Welsh  ,   Walsh  . The idea that the Scottish surname refers to the Welsh-speaking Britons of Strathclyde is erroneous."]},{"name":"Welshans","meanings":["Irish: derivative of   Welsh  , with Irish diminutive <i>-an</i> and English excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. John Welsh was born in 1229, in Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom. She had at least 2 daughters with Sir John Welsh."},"et":{"1229–Deceased":"1229–Surnud","1225–1280":"1225–1280","1240–Female":"1240–Surnud","1254–Female":"1254–Surnud","1229–Female":"1229–Surnud","1225":"1225","1254":"1254","1240":"1240","1280":"1280","1229":"1229","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1229–Deceased":"1229–Kuollut","1225–1280":"1225–1280","1240–Female":"1240–Kuollut","1254–Female":"1254–Kuollut","1229–Female":"1229–Kuollut","1225":"1225","1254":"1254","1240":"1240","1280":"1280","1229":"1229","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1229–Deceased":"1229–Décédée","1225–1280":"1225–1280","1240–Female":"1240–Décédée","1254–Female":"1254–Décédée","1229–Female":"1229–Décédée","1225":"1225","1254":"1254","1240":"1240","1280":"1280","1229":"1229","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Mrs. John Welsh est née en 1229, à Glamorgan, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 2 filles avec Sir John Welsh."},"de":{"1229–Deceased":"1229–Verstorben","1225–1280":"1225–1280","1240–Female":"1240–Verstorben","1254–Female":"1254–Verstorben","1229–Female":"1229–Verstorben","1225":"1225","1254":"1254","1240":"1240","1280":"1280","1229":"1229","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Mrs. John Welsh wurde 1229 in